 and its aftermath. Also assembled together for the first time is a collection of primary documents – including government reports, parliamentary debates, and redress movement statements – prefaced with contextual information. Reconciling Canada provides a vital and immensely relevant illumination of the dynamics of reconciliation, apology, and redress in contemporary Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aReconciliation (Law)zCanada. 0aReparations for historical injusticeszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aCarastathis, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCho, Lily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDean, Amber, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmberley, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFindlay, Len, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLedohowski, Lindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackey, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiki, Roy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMillion, Dian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimon, Roger I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurner, Dale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWakeham, Pauline , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWakeham, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoungblood Henderson, James Sa’ke’j, econt